# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-english
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-english/24-7] In commerce and industry, **24/7** or **24-7 service** (usually pronounced "twenty-four seven") is service that is available at any time of day, 24 hours, and every day of the week, 7 days.
[src:american-english/24-7] An alternate orthography is **24×7** (usually pronounced "twenty-four by seven").
[src:american-english/24-7] Less commonly used are the terms **24/7/52** (adding "52 weeks") and **24/7/365** (adding "365 days") make it clear that service is available every day of the year including the one extra day on leap years.
[src:american-english/24-7] Synonyms include **around-the-clock service** (with/without hyphens) and **all day every day**, especially in British English, and **nonstop service**, but the latter can also refer to other things, such as public transport services which go between two stations without stopping.
[src:american-english/24-7] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (OED) defines the term as "twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week; constantly".
[src:american-english/24-7] It lists its first reference to 24/7 to be from a 1983 story in the US magazine *Sports Illustrated* in which Louisiana State University basketball player Jerry Reynolds describes his jump shot in just such a way: 24–7–365.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 service is employed in many settings including commercial businesses, emergency services, transport, utilities, certain industrial processes, and some human services.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 services may also include taxicabs, security services, and in densely populated urban areas, construction crews.
[src:american-english/24-7] Public 24/7 services often include those provided by emergency medical providers, police, fire and emergency telephone numbers, such as 9-1-1 in North America.
[src:american-english/24-7] Transport services like airports, airlines, and ferry services, and in some cases trains and buses, may provide 24-hour service.
[src:american-english/24-7] Examples of public transport services operating 24/7 include the New York City Subway, Staten Island Railway, PATH, PATCO, the Copenhagen Metro, and the Red Line and Blue Line of the Chicago "L".
[src:american-english/24-7] Many networks run a reduced night service schedule.
[src:american-english/24-7] Industrial and manufacturing facilities—especially those that operate near or at capacity, or which depend upon processes (such as production lines) that are costly to suspend—often provide 24/7 services.
[src:american-english/24-7] Similarly, utilities generally must provide multiple 24/7 services.
[src:american-english/24-7] For instance, an electricity provider will handle outage reports 24/7 and dispatch emergency repair technicians 24/7, in addition to monitoring electrical infrastructure and producing electricity at all times.
[src:american-english/24-7] The same applies to telecommunications and internet service providers.
[src:american-english/24-7] Many crisis centers and crisis hotlines provide 24/7 services.
[src:american-english/24-7] Many 24/7 services operate continuously at all times with complete shift staff.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 services that can utilize virtual offices, such as call centers, may employ daytime agents in alternating time zones.
[src:american-english/24-7] In some cases, 24/7 services may be temporarily unavailable under certain circumstances.
[src:american-english/24-7] Such scenarios may include scheduled maintenance, upgrades or renovation, emergency repair, and injunction.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 services which depend upon the physical presence of employees at a given location may also be interrupted when a minimum number of employees cannot be present due to scenarios such as extreme weather, death threats, natural disasters, or mandatory evacuation.
[src:american-english/24-7] Some 24/7 services close during major holidays.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 services often employ complex schemes that ensure their resistance to potential disruption, resilience in the event of disruption, and minimum standards of overall reliability.
[src:american-english/24-7] Critical infrastructure may be supported by failover systems, electric generators, and satellite communications.
[src:american-english/24-7] In the event of catastrophic disaster, some 24/7 services prepare entirely redundant, parallel infrastructures, often in other geographic regions.
[src:american-english/24-7] At the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, many stores ended 24/7 operations, ostensibly on a temporary basis, in order to clean and sanitize their establishments.
[src:american-english/24-7] After the widespread availability of vaccines, however, many such businesses have not returned to 24-hour service for a variety of reasons.
[src:american-english/24-7] Some proprietors in the United States originally blamed pandemic unemployment benefits for a lack of workers, yet employers still struggled to resume pre-pandemic hours after these programs ended, citing continued staff shortages and demands for better working conditions among jobseekers.
[src:american-english/24-7] Many businesses that were once broadly open for 24/7 operations only resumed such service across some of their establishments or have ended 24/7 operations altogether, as in the case of Walmart.
[src:american-english/24-7] 24/7 workplaces can put employees under conditions that limit their personal life choices and development.
[src:american-english/24-7] Calls for a rehumanisation of the 24/7 workplace have therefore been voiced.
[src:american-english/24-7] Some have also remarked on the "collective mania" especially in the US that takes a sort of pride in the "work at all times" attitude exemplified by the 24/7 concept.
[src:american-english/24-7] In England, Wales, and Northern Ireland, the Sunday trading laws prevent many stores from truly opening 24/7, but they sometimes advertise as such.
[src:american-english/24-7] Some core services such as filling stations are exempt from the law requiring them to close.
[src:american-english/24-7] A campaign against changing the law was supported by many bodies, including the Church of England, the Church in Wales, and many secular bodies in an effort called Keep Sunday Special.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is distinct from other accents in its county, such as the one spoken in Myddfai, due to separation by the Brecon Beacons, creating a substantial communication barrier between the two localities.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] It is more appropriate to associate it with neighbouring Swansea Valley, particularly the speech in northern areas (esp.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Ystalyfera and Ystradgynlais) since they are more similar to Abercraf than ones in its county.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] This could be seen from a survey where speakers could not discern the origins of the speech of Ystradgynlais and their hometown, but were able to discern Cwmtwrch with other villages in the valley.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf was entirely Welsh-speaking until World War II, when English-speaking evacuees settled in the village.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] It is a relatively young acquired dialect.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] This can be seen from generally less assimilation and elision and clear articulation unlike other accents in Powys or Swansea.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] As a more modern accent, it is restricted to the last two to three generations, with younger people being much more likely to speak it — though much of their daily life is conducted in Welsh, leading English to be taught as a second language.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is non-rhotic; /r/ is only pronounced before a vowel.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Like RP, linking and intrusive R is present in the system.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] On the other hand, the vowel system varies greatly from RP, unlike its consonants, which is stable in many English accents around the world.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] The offsets of the fronting diphthongs are near-close [ɪ], whereas the offsets of the backing diphthongs are close [u].
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf has kept some distinctions between diphthong–monophthong pronunciations; they are shared among other south Welsh dialects such as Port Talbot.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English generally follows West Glamorgan lexical incidence patterns.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] The vowel /ə/ is not elided, thus *factory*, *mandarin*, *reference* always have three syllables, unlike many accents such as RP or even Port Talbot.
[src:american-english/abercraf-english] Abercraf English is considered to have a 'sing-song' or 'lilting' intonation due to having high amount of pitch on an unstressed post-tonic syllable, as well as pre-tonic syllables having a great degree of freedom, with a continuous rising pitch being common.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case, which confirmed the May 2022 leaks obtained by *Politico* and overruled *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The American Historical Association (AHA) and the Organization of American Historians (OAH) were among those who signed an *amici curiae* brief for *Dobbs*, and were cited, among others, by *Reason*, *Syracuse University News*, and *The Washington Post*.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Joined by at least 30 other academic and scholarly institutions, they condemned "the court's misinterpretation about the history of legalized abortion" and said it has "the potential to exacerbate historic injustices and deepen inequalities in our country".
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the wake of state abortion bans and restrictions in the United States, Americans have started traveling to Mexico for abortions, and Mexico has expressed a willingness to help.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Providers openly treat American travelers in several states where abortion remains technically illegal, such as Nuevo Leon, which neighbors Texas.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Following the Supreme Court ruling, abortion is being gradually legalized at the state level, and as of 2025 is legal during the first trimester (before the 13th week after implantation) in twenty states and Mexico City.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Although it is uncommon, women sometimes give birth in spite of an attempted abortion.
[src:american-english/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Reporting of live birth after attempted abortion may not be consistent from state to state, but 38 were recorded in one study in upstate New York in the two-and-a-half years before *Roe v.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect levelling has been observed in most languages with large numbers of speakers after industrialization and modernization of the areas in which they are spoken.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Leonard Bloomfield implicitly distinguished between the short-term process of accommodation between speakers and the long-term process of levelling between varieties and between the social and the geographical dimensions.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] On the geographical dimension, levelling may disrupt the regularity that is the result of the application of sound laws.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It operates in waves but may leave behind relic forms.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect levelling and *Mischung*, or dialect mixing, have been suggested as the key mechanisms that destroy regularity and the alleged exceptionlessness of sound laws.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect levelling is triggered by contact between dialects, often because of migration, and it has been observed in most languages with large numbers of speakers after the industrialisation and the modernisation of the area or areas in which they are spoken.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It results in unique features of dialects being eliminated and "may occur over several generations until a stable compromise dialect develops".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It is separate from the levelling of variation between dialectal or vernacular versions of a language and standard versions.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Contact leading to dialect levelling can stem from geographical and social mobility, which brings together speakers from different regions and social levels.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Adolescents can drive levelling, as they adapt their speech under the influence of their peers, rather than their parents.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In 20th-century British English, dialect levelling was caused by social upheaval leading to larger social networks.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Agricultural advancements caused movement from rural to urban areas, and the construction of suburbs caused city-dwellers to return to former rural areas.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The World Wars brought women into the workforce and men into contact with more diverse backgrounds.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] While written and spoken language can diverge significantly, the presence of long distance communication – which prior to inventions such as the telephone was virtually always written – usually drives or necessitates the use of a lingua franca, dialect levelling or both.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] To be understood by their correspondence partners farther away, authors will naturally tend to reduce exceedingly local forms and incorporate loanwords from the dialect of the person they're writing to.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] If enough such correspondence is undertaken over a long enough time frame by enough people a new written standard or *de facto* standard can emerge.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Examples include Middle Low German as employed by the Hanseatic League or Koine Greek.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In the absence of long distance communication and travel, languages and dialects can diverge significantly in comparatively short time spans.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It has been suggested that dialect levelling plays a role in the formation of creoles.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It is responsible for standardising the multiple language variants that are produced by the relexification of substrate languages with words from the lexifier language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Features that are not common to all of the substrata and so are different across the varieties of the emerging creole tend to be eliminated.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The process begins "when the speakers of the creole community stop targeting the lexifier language and start targeting the relexified lexicons, that is, the early creole".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect levelling in such a situation may not be complete, however.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Variation that remains after dialect levelling may result in the "reallocation" of surviving variants to "new functions, such as stylistic or social markers".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Also, differences between substrata, including between dialects of a single substratum, may not be levelled at all but instead persist, as differences between dialects of the creole.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] New Zealand English is a relatively new native variety of English.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The English language was brought to the islands in 1800 but became influential only in the 1840s because of large-scale migration from Britain.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The most distinctive part of the language is the formation of the accent that has developed through complex series of processes involving dialect contact between different varieties of British English, followed by dialect mixture.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Although New Zealand English sounds very similar to Australian English, it is not a direct transplant, as Australians were only 7% of the immigrants before 1881, and the majority of the linguistic change in New Zealand English happened between 1840 and 1880.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The speed with which New Zealand English became a unique, independent form of English can be attributed to the diversity of speakers who came into contact through colonisation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Features from all over the British Isles and the Māori people, who had inhabited the island for 600 years prior to colonisation, can be identified in the form that New Zealand English has taken.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Rudimentary levelling in New Zealand English occurred around 1860, the result of contact between adult speakers of different regional and social varieties and the accommodation that was required from the speakers in face-to-face interaction.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Settlements attracted people from all walks of life and created highly-diverse linguistic variation, but there were still families that lived in almost total isolation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Thus, the children did not gain the dialect of their peers, as was normally expected, but instead maintained the dialect of their parents.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Speakers who grow up in that type of situation are more likely to demonstrate intra-individual variability than speakers whose main source of influence is their peers.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] When the emerging dialect stabilises, it is the result of a focusing process, which allowed for a very small amount of regional variation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] New Zealand English is largely based around the typology and forms of southeastern England because of the levelling out of demographic minority dialect forms.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The process may take an extended length of time.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Reduction then takes place as the result of group accommodation between speakers in face-to-face interaction.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Accommodation may also lead to the development of interdialectal forms, forms that are not present in contributing dialects but may be the result of hyperadaptation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In this case study, Hinskens (1998) researches dialect levelling in the Dutch province of Limburg.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Based on his findings, he argues that dialect levelling does not necessarily lead to convergence towards the standard language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The research for this case study takes place in Rimburg, a small village on the southeast of Limburg, where Ripuarian dialects are spoken.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The southeast area of Limburg experienced rapid industrialisation at the turn of the 20th century with the largescale development of coal mining.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] That created job opportunities, which led to considerable immigration to the area (Hinskens:38), which, in turn, led to language contact and a diversification of language varieties.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It is the area where most of the dialect levelling occurred.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Geographically, the dialects of Limburg are divided into three zones.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The westernmost zone (C-zone) features East-Limburg dialects, the easternmost zone (A-zone) Ripuarian dialects, with the central zone (B-zone) being a transition zone between the two varieties.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] As one travels from west to east, the dialect features deviate more and more from the standard language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Additionally, the dialect features accumulate from west to east and features found in East-Limburg dialects are also found in Ripuarian dialects but not the other way around (Hinskens 1998:37).
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The study found that "the ratio of dialect features showing overall loss to dialect features investigated decreases with increasing geographical distribution" (Hinskels:43).
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In other words, the wider the distribution of the dialectal feature, the less likely that it will level with the standard language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] For example, dialectal features found in all three zones, such as /t/ deletion, were maintained, and features such as the postlexical ɣ-weakening, which occurs only in the Ripuarian dialects (A-zone), were lost.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Of the 21 features that are analysed, 14 resulted in a loss of a dialect feature.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Some of the features that were levelled did not lead to convergence toward the standard language and, in some cases, there was even divergence (Hinksens:45).
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] "Rimburg dialect is in the process of adopting the morpho-phonemics of the surrounding B-zone dialects," rather than Standard Dutch (Hinskens:27).
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect levelling in this case cannot be explained in terms of convergence with the standard language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The study concludes that dialect levelling resulted from accommodation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] "Accommodation and dialect levelling should be understood in the light of the continuous struggle between... the tendencies towards unification on the one hand and those towards particularism and cultural fragmentation on the other" (Hinskens:42).
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Those who spoke the same dialect were part of the in-group, and those who spoke a different variety were part of the out-group.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Based on conversation data, Hinskens found that "the more typical/unique a dialect feature is for a speaker's dialect, the larger the relative number of linguistic conditions in which the use of this dialect feature is suppressed in out-group contact situations".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Accommodation, or suppression of dialect features, then facilitates mutual comprehension and results in the convergence of dialect features.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The emergence of Standard German was a complicated process because no German dialect had significantly more prestige than any other – partly due to political fractionation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Only relatively recently has a dialect attained sufficient prestige for it to be widely adopted.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Old High German (OHG) is an umbrella term to encompass what are in reality numerous divergent dialects – sometimes with hardly any mutual intelligibility.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] While it was without a doubt *þiudisk, that is the language of common folk (*þiudisk is the origin of the modern words deutsch and Dutch), it was not a useful means of long distance communication.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Few people could read and write, parchment was expensive and those who could write usually read enough Latin to bridge the dialect gap that way – similar to how Dutch and German people may communicate with one another in English to bridge the dialect gap nowadays.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Nonetheless, some monasteries and the Carolingian court did produce some vernacular writing, most of which was lost, but the remains of which form almost the entirety of the OHG corpus.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] After 1022 little written material in the vernacular was produced for a century, so a significantly changed language would reemerge when vernacular writing resumed.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Any even tentative hints of dialect leveling in the OHG period were in essence reset to zero.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] What is now called Middle High German was still clearly divided into dialects (e.g. the Niebelungenlied was written in a Bavarian dialect) but due to the prestige of the Hohenstaufen dynasty a certain convergence can be observed in the language used by authors enjoying imperial patronage.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] However, with the end of the Hohenstaufen, centralizing tendencies in both politics and linguistics came to a halt in the Holy Roman Empire and there was no longer an imperial patronage for poetry.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Interestingly, the Hohenstaufen era dialect leveling seemed to converge on a standard with some elements in common with modern Alemanic.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Today the Alemanic-derived Swiss German is often deemed the most divergent dialect under the Standard German Dachsprache.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] There is today a clear distinction between "High German" dialects which had undergone the Second Germanic consonant shift and "Low German" dialects which had not.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] However, this dichotomy oversimplifies matters as it ignores the "Middle German" dialects which sit on the "Low German" side of some isoglosses and the "High German" side of others.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Standardization did not get fully underway until 13th-century Franciscans began a push to establish a literate public; however, at this time, 70% of the materials produced were in Medieval Latin, as opposed to German.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The lingua franca of much of the Baltic Sea Coast in the heyday of the Hanse was Middle Low German.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] However, as the Hanseatic League began to weaken by the 16th century, its potential to drive linguistic unity was reduced.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] During the 14th and 15th centuries, the language underwent a massive phonological shift, and these changes are still visible linguistic features today.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Eastern Central Germany was at the center of the changes and became a linguistically uniform area, which set it apart from other parts of the German-speaking world that remained linguistically diverse.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The Viennese imperial chancellery introduced influential spelling reforms, but most regions maintained their own systems, which resulted in five varieties of "printer's language" being used in publications.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] While administration in prior eras had been handled largely in Latin and produced orders of magnitude less written material, the inventing of movable type printing and the widespread availability of cheap paper enabled a "bureaucratic revolution".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] However, the question of standardization soon arose and so each state bureaucracy (then known as a chancery) set "house standards" for orthography which were based at least in part on the spoken language of locally recruited staff.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Now at least those in the wider area of a chancery with a high prestige standard had a written koine language that would be understood by all literate people within the area.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The spoken language, however, underwent virtually no standardization within that era.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The largest influence in the 16th century was Martin Luther.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Besides theological disagreements with the Vatican, his main contention was that every Christian should have access to theological texts in the vernacular.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] For this to succeed, two conditions had to be met: rapid distribution of the new translation at affordable prices (achievable thanks to printing) and a written vernacular that would be understood by as many people as possible.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] He did not create a new dialect for this task; most of his work was written in the language of Upper Saxony's chancellery based in Meißen, which was very close to his native dialect.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Due to the prestige of that language, his work was more widely accepted.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] He was also able to influence the lexicon, both in choice of vocabulary and semantic selections.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Since so many people read his work, orthography began to stabilize and with a canonical Standard German corpus of sorts being developed, although this was largely limited to the Protestant north.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Despite the religious differences between the north and south of Germany, it was the existence of Eastern Central German that prevented the initial spread of Luther's linguistic forms.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] This divide was overcome in the Protestant parts of Central Germany as the prestige of Luther's dialect assured the acceptance of features from Eastern Central German.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The differences were further reduced, as the need for coherent written communication became paramount and Eastern Central German, now highly identified with Luther, became the linguistic medium of the north.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Low German, once the first language of the region and a subject of instruction, was displaced and restricted to use in comedic theater, and even there, it was used only by important figures.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The first editions of Luther's bible translation still contained glosses for terms that might not be regionally understood — the effect of his work was so immense that those glosses were left out of later editions within Luther's lifetime as they were no longer deemed necessary.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] To this day, the by now almost five centuries old Luther Bible is preferred by some Lutherans in Germany over more modern translations and it is generally seen as one of the earliest texts in the Early New High German stage of the now increasingly standardizing German written language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] This shift allowed "language societies" to modify the language further in the 17th century by translating Latinate compounds using German morphemes, which could be understood by any German-speaking child.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Grammarians developed a body of usage within the canonical corpus, which was evaluated to monitor the use of the language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It was then that the *ge*-prefix for non-auxiliary past participles was regularized.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Linguistic purism was also an issue, with French terms in particular being the target of deliberate attempts to replace them – many of them successful but others not.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The most notable group of linguistic purists in Germany during that era was the fruchtbringende Gesellschaft.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The middle of the 18th century produced a slew of northern writers, who would ultimately shape the interaction between Catholic Germany, which had resisted Luther's linguistic influence, and the rest of the German-speaking world, directing the language's development path.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The south did not have any comparable literary innovators to counterbalance the sudden emergence of standardized language in the north, so for two generations, the south's most influential literary minds spoke Lutheran-influenced dialects.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In 1871, after centuries of highly-variable spelling and punctuation, a conference was held to create a uniform framework for German spelling, steered by the publication of a Bavarian dictionary in 1879 and a Prussian dictionary in 1880.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Similar to the abortive attempts to create a *singular* German language standard in the High Middle Ages, it would again be poets enjoying court patronage that gave the impetus for a standardized *pronunciation* of the written form.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] For the luminaries of Weimar Classicism, it would just not do, that a play *written* the same way all throughout German lands would *sound* different in Goethe's native Frankfurt to Schiller's native Württemberg to their adoptive Weimar.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] So the deutsche Bühnenaussprache was developed — initially intended for theater only, it would become the standard for radio, television and whenever someone from out of town tried to get understood by the locals.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Jacob Grimm and Rudolf von Raumer created controversy in the 19th century, as they proposed conflicting criteria for defining spelling.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Grimm argued that history and etymology should determine spelling, but van Raumer claimed that spelling should be based on pronunciation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Grimm's historical case found its way into orthography, with two different spellings of final /p, t, t-x/, depending on the surrounding environments.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Any sort of standard pronunciation, therefore, was heavily reliant on standard writing.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Kjeld Kristensen and Mats Thelander discuss two socio-dialectal investigations, one Danish and one Swedish.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The paper suggests that the development of urban society and an increasing degree of publicness were mentioned as important non-linguistic causes of the accelerating dialect levelling.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The levelling of dialects of Danish towards the metropolitan standard of Copenhagen has been dubbed **Copenhagenization** by Tore Kristiansen.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In this case study, Anderson (2002) discusses dialect levelling of African American Vernacular English (AAVE) spoken in Detroit.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In her research, she analyzes a very particular linguistic variable, the monophthongization of /aɪ/ before voiceless obstruents.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] While monophthongization of the diphthong /aɪ > aː/ is common in AAVE, it generally occurs in the environment of voiced, not voiceless, obstruents.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] For example, a southern speaker of AAVE would pronounce the word *tide* (voiced obstruent) as [taːd] and pronounce the word *tight* (voiceless obstruent) as [taɪt], but some southern white speakers would pronounce it as [taːt].
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The monophthongization of /aɪ/ before voiceless obstruents is a salient characteristic of southern white dialects such as Appalachian and Texas varieties of English, and in the southern states, it indexes group membership with southern white people.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] To the north, however, in Detroit, the linguistic feature does not mark group membership with white people.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Anderson presents evidence that this linguistic marker has been adopted among speakers of AAVE in Detroit, in part because of contact with white Appalachian immigrants.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In other words, the diphthongization of /aɪ/ before voiced obstruents, which is a common feature of AAVE, has been levelled with that of southern white dialects and is now then being pronounced as a monophthong.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In her article, Anderson reports that black and white segregation in Detroit is higher than in any other American city.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] She describes the demographics stating that the overwhelming majority of white people have moved to the suburbs and most local black people live in the inner city of Detroit (pp.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] White Appalachians who have migrated to Detroit have found refuge in the inner city and have maintained close ties with black people.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] That is partly because of their cultural orientation to the South but also because both groups have been marginalised and, hence, subject to discrimination.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The contact among them has led to the levelling of AAVE with a southern white variety in which speakers of AAVE have adopted the monophthongization of /aɪ/ before voiceless obstruents.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In the South, the linguistic marker indexes group membership between black people and white people, but in the North, the linguistic marker no longer works since white Detroiters do not use this feature in their speech.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Anderson concludes that "the overall effect is that Detroit AAVE aligns with a Southern vowel system for the /ai/ vowel variable, including that of the Detroit Southern White community, while indexing an opposition with Northern Whites" (p.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] A study of Mandarin leveling in Taiwan investigated the tonal leveling of Mandarin between Mandarin-Waishengren (外省人) and Holo-Benshengren (本省人) in Taiwan.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The results indicated that the tonal leveling of Mandarin between these two ethnic groups started one generation earlier than the general patterns suggested by Trudgill.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] This leveling has nearly reached its completion in the following generation, taking approximately 30 years.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The frequent contacts between Waishengren and Benshengren.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Language convergence refers to what can happen linguistically when speakers adapt "to the speech of others to reduce differences".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] As such, it is a type of accommodation (modification), namely the opposite of divergence, which is the exploitation and making quantitatively more salient of differences.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] One can imagine this to be a long-term effect of interspeaker accommodation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Like interference, dialect levelling is a contact phenomenon.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] However, it cannot be considered to be a type of interference according to Weinreich (1953), since (a) it is not a concomitant of bilingualism, and (b) it is not merely a performance phenomenon.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Dialect leveling need not produce a new usage, but it may very well result in qualitative changes.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Geographical diffusion is the process by which linguistic features spread out from a populous and economically and culturally dominant centre.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The spread is generally wave-like, but modified by the likelihood that nearby towns and cities will adopt the feature before the more rural parts in between.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] At the individual level in such a diffusion model, speakers are in face-to-face contact with others who have already adopted the new feature, and (for various reasons) they are motivated to adopt it themselves.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The reduction or attrition of marked variants in this case brings about levelling.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Kerswill mentions that standardisation does not necessarily follow from dialect levelling; it is perfectly possible for dialects to converge without getting closer to the standard, which does happen in some situations.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The mechanism for standardisation lies in the kinds of social networks people have.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] People with more broadly based (more varied) networks will meet people with a higher social status.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] They will accommodate to them in a phenomenon known as upward convergence.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] The opposite, downward convergence, where a higher-status person accommodates to a lower status person, is much rarer.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] This accommodation is thought to happen mainly among adults in Western societies, not children or adolescents, because in those societies children and adolescents have much more self-centred, narrower peer groups.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] In societies where standardisation is generally something that adults do, children and adolescents perform other kinds of levelling.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Accommodation between individual speakers of different dialects takes place with respect to features that are salient, displaying phonetic or surface phonemic contrasts between the dialects.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] This process is mostly limited to salient features, geographical (distance), and demographic (population size) factors.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Accommodation is not the same thing as levelling, but it can be its short-term preamble.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Koinéization, unlike dialect levelling, "involves the mixing of features of different dialects, and leads to a new, compromised dialect".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] It results from "integration or unification of the speakers of the varieties in contact".
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Clearly, dialect levelling is not strictly synonymous with koinéisation.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] First, dialect levelling does not merely take place in the space between dialects; it may also occur between a dialect and a standard language.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] Second, its end product cannot be equated with that of koinéisation, a koiné being the structurally stabilized and sociologically more or less standard product of heavy intermixture.
[src:american-english/accent-leveling] According to Milroy (2002), the difference between dialect levelling and koinéization is that dialect levelling involves the eradication of linguistic variants due to language contact while koinéization involves the creation of a new linguistic variety based on language contact.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In sociolinguistics, an **accent** is a way of pronouncing a language that is distinctive to a country, area, social class, or individual.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] An accent may be identified with the locality in which its speakers reside (a regional or geographical accent), the socioeconomic status of its speakers, their ethnicity (an ethnolect), their caste or social class (a social accent), or influence from their first language (a foreign accent).
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents typically differ in quality of voice, pronunciation and distinction of vowels and consonants, stress, and prosody.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Although grammar, semantics, vocabulary, and other language characteristics often vary concurrently with accent, the word "accent" may refer specifically to the differences in pronunciation, whereas the word "dialect" encompasses the broader set of linguistic differences.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] "Accent" is often a subset of "dialect".
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] As human beings spread out into isolated communities, stresses and peculiarities develop.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Over time, they can develop into identifiable accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In North America, the interaction of people from many ethnic backgrounds contributed to the formation of the different varieties of North American accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] It is difficult to measure or predict how long it takes an accent to form.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents from Canada, South Africa, Australia and the United States for example, developed from the combinations of different accents and languages in various societies and their effect on the various pronunciations of British settlers.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents may vary within regions of an area in which a uniform language is spoken.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In some cases, such as regional accents of English in the United States, accents can be traced back to when an area was settled and by whom.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Areas like the city of New Orleans in Louisiana that are, or at one point in time were, semi-isolated have distinct accents due to the absence of contact between regions.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Isolated regions allow dialects to expand and evolve independently.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Social and economic factors can also influence the way people speak.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] During the early period of rapid cognitive development in a child's life, it is much easier to develop and master foreign skills such as learning a new (or first) language.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Verbal cues are processed and silently learned in preparation for the day the vocal system is developed enough to speak its first words (usually around 12 months).
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Before infants can identify words, they just hear "sounds" that they come to recognize.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Eventually neural pathways are established in the brain that link each sound with a meaning.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The more frequently a word is heard, the more its connection is solidified and the same goes for accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] There is no "standard" accent for the child to practice; as far as they are concerned, the accent they hear from their parents is not the "right" way but the only way.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Eventually children graduate from the conscious act of recalling each word, and it becomes natural, like breathing.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] As children grow up, they learn vocabulary of the language they are immersed in, whether assisted by parents or not.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] However, their first few encounters with words determine the way they will pronounce them for the rest of their lives.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] This is how accents are cultivated in groups as small as towns and as large as countries; it is a compounding effect.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Though it is possible to develop a new accent or lose an old one, it is difficult because the neural pathways created when learning the language were developed with the "original" pronunciations.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Children are able to take on accents relatively quickly.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Children of immigrant families, for example, generally have a pronunciation more similar to people native to where they live compared to their parents, but both children and parents may have an accent noticeably differing from local people.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents seem to remain relatively malleable until a person's early twenties, after which a person's accent seems to become more entrenched.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Nonetheless, accents are not fixed even in adulthood.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] An acoustic analysis by Jonathan Harrington of Elizabeth II's Royal Christmas Messages revealed that the speech patterns of even so conservative a figure as a monarch can continue to change over her lifetime.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents of non-native speakers may be the result of the speaker's native language.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Each language contains distinct sets of sounds.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] At around 12 months, human infants will pick out which sounds they need to learn their language.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] As they get older, it becomes increasingly harder to learn these "forgotten" sounds.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] A prime example of this can be seen between German and English: the "w" and "th" sounds, like in the English words "wish" and "this" respectively, do not exist in German (the closest sounds are "v" because a German “w” is rendered as a “v”, and "z" because the “th” sounds do not exist in German).
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] As a result, many English-speaking Germans pronounce "wish" as "vish" and "this" as "zis".
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] A similar disjunction occurs in German-speaking native English speakers, who may find it difficult to pronounce the vowels in German words such as "schön" (beautiful) and "müde" (tired).
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] An important factor in predicting the degree to which the accent will be noticeable (or strong) is the age at which the non-native language was learned.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The critical period theory states that if learning takes place after the critical period (usually considered around puberty) for acquiring native-like pronunciation, an individual is unlikely to acquire a native-like accent.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] This theory, however, is quite controversial among researchers.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Nevertheless, children as young as 6 at the time of moving to another country often speak with a noticeable non-native accent as adults.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] There are also rare instances of individuals who are able to pass for native speakers even if they learned their non-native language in early adulthood.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] However, neurological constraints associated with brain development appear to limit most non-native speakers' ability to sound native-like.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Most researchers agree that for most adults, acquiring a native-like accent in a non-native language is near impossible.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] When a group defines a standard pronunciation, speakers who deviate from it are often said to "speak with an accent".
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] However, everyone speaks with an accent.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] People from the United States would "speak English with an accent" from the point of view of an Australian, and vice versa.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents such as Received Pronunciation or General American English may sometimes be erroneously designated in their countries of origin as "accentless" to indicate that they offer no obvious clue to the speaker's regional or social background.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents are an important dimension of social identity, both individual and communal, due to their ability to identify group or community belonging.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] One's accent can showcase their class, religion or sexual orientation.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Many teachers of English as a second language for example neglect teaching speech and pronunciation.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Many adult and near-adult learners of second languages have unintelligible speech patterns that may interfere with their education, profession, and social interactions.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Pronunciation in a second or foreign language involves more than the correct articulation of individual sounds.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] It involves producing a wide range of complex and subtle distinctions which relate sound to meaning at several levels.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Inadequate instruction in speech/pronunciation can result in a complete breakdown in communication.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The proliferation of commercial "accent reduction" services is seen as a sign that many ESL teachers are not meeting their students' needs for speech/pronunciation instruction.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The goals of speech/pronunciation instruction should include: to help the learner speak in a way that is easy to understand and does not distract the listener, to increase the self-confidence of the learner, and to develop the skills to self-monitor and adapt one's own speech.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Even when the listener does understand the speaker, the presence of an accent that is difficult to understand can produce anxiety in the listener that he will not understand what comes next, and cause him to end the conversation earlier or avoid difficult topics.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] "In speech the perceptual salience of the accent overrides other measures of competence and performance," wrote Ingrid Piller.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Intelligibility of speech, in comparison to native-like accent, has been experimentally reported to be of greater importance for the second language speakers.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] As such ways of increasing intelligibility of speech has been recommended by some researchers within the field.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] A strong accent does not necessarily impede intelligibility despite common perceptions.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Certain accents, particularly those of European heritage, are perceived to carry more prestige in a society than other accents, such that some speakers may as a result consciously adopt them.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] This is often due to their association with the elite part of society.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] For example, in the United Kingdom, Received Pronunciation of the English language is associated with the traditional upper class.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The goal of linguistics with respect to accents is to catalogue them and to track, explain, and, occasionally, predict their evolution.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In the process, linguistics recognizes that the assignment of differing levels of prestige, aesthetic merit, and/or "standardness" by different sectors of society to different accents influences the evolution of those accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] However, linguistics, at least in its ideal form, does not itself participate in making those normative assessments and comparisons.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Negative perceptions of accents, the basis of which may relate to the speaker's social identity, can manifest as stereotyping, harassment or employment discrimination.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Researchers consistently show that people with non-native accents are judged as less intelligent, less competent, less educated, having poor English/language skills, and unpleasant to listen to.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Not only people with standard accents subscribe to these beliefs and attitudes, but individuals with accents also often stereotype against their own or others' accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Research demonstrates that an average listener is adept at detecting an accent typical of a language differing from their own.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents have even found to be more impactful on perception of babies than known perceptual dividers like race, religion, or sex.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In a *PNAS* study, babies were told to choose a toy from two recorded speakers with varying characteristics.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Ahead of all variables tested, including race and gender, recordings speaking with an accent native to the child were selected at a considerably higher frequency.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Unlike other forms of discrimination, there are no strong norms against accent discrimination in the general society.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In the English speaking world, speakers with certain accents often experience discrimination in housing and employment.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] For example, speakers who have foreign or ethnic-minority accents are less likely to be called back by landlords and are more likely to be assigned by employers to lower status positions than those with standard accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In business settings, individuals with non-standard accents are more likely to be evaluated negatively.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accent discrimination is also present in educational institutions.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] For example, non-native speaking graduate students, lecturers, and professors, across college campuses in the US have been targeted for being unintelligible because of accent.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Second language speakers have reported being discriminated against, or feeling marginalized for, when they attempted to find a job in higher ranking positions mainly because of their accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] On average, however, students taught by non-native English speakers do not underperform when compared to those taught by native speakers of English.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Some English native-speaker students in Canada reported a preference for non-native speaker instructors as long as the instructor's speech is intelligible.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] This was due to the psychological impacts such circumstances has on the students requiring them to pay closer attention to the instructor to ensure they understand them.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Studies have shown the perception of the accent, not the accent by itself, often results in negative evaluations of speakers.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In a study conducted by Rubin (1992), students listened to a taped lecture recorded by a native English speaker with a standard accent.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] They were then shown an image of the "lecturer", sometimes Asian-looking, sometimes white.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Participants in the study who saw the Asian picture believed that they had heard an accented lecturer and performed worse on a task that measured lecture comprehension.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Negative evaluations may reflect the prejudices rather than real issues with understanding accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] In the United States, Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits discrimination based on national origin, implying accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] However, employers may claim that a person's accent impairs their communication skills that are necessary to the effective business operation.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] The courts often rely on the employer's claims or use judges' subjective opinions when deciding whether the (potential) employee's accent would interfere with communication or performance, without any objective proof that accent was or might be a hindrance.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Kentucky's highest court in the case of *Clifford vs.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Commonwealth* held that a white police officer, who had not seen the black defendant allegedly involved in a drug transaction, could, nevertheless, identify him as a participant by saying that a voice on an audiotape "sounded black".
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Actors are often called upon to speak a language variety other than their own.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] For instance, an actor may portray a character of some nationality other than their own by adopting into their native language the phonological profile typical of the nationality to be portrayed, in what is commonly known as "speaking with an accent".
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Accents may have stereotypical associations in entertainment.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] For example, in Disney animated films, mothers and fathers typically speak with White, middle-class American or English accents.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] On another note, English accents in Disney animated films are frequently employed for one of two purposes: slapstick comedy and the portrayal of evil geniuses.
[src:american-english/accent-sociolinguistics] Examples of this can be seen in characters from the films *Aladdin* (the Sultan and Jafar, respectively) and *The Lion King* (Zazu and Scar, respectively), among others.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The **Achumawi language** (also **Achomawi** or **Pit River language**) is the indigenous language spoken by the Pit River people in the northeast corner of present-day California.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The term Achumawi is an anglicization of the name of the Fall River band, *ajúmmááwí*, from *ajúmmá* 'river'.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Originally there were nine bands, with dialect differences primarily between upriver (Atwamwi, Astariwawi; Kosalektawi, Hammawi, Hewisedawi dialects) and downriver (Madesiwi, Itsatawi, Ilmawi, and Achumawi (proper) dialects), demarcated by the Big Valley mountains east of the Fall River valley.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Together, Achumawi and Atsugewi are said to comprise the Palaihnihan language family separate from the adjacent and related Shastan family.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The basis of this grouping is weakened by poor quality of data.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] David Olmsted's data dictionary depends almost entirely upon de Angulo, and carelessly includes Pomo vocabulary from a manuscript in which he (de Angulo) set out to demonstrate that Achumawi and Pomo are not related.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] William Bright and Shirley Silver questioned Olmsted's results and methods of reconstruction.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The phenomenon of non-reciprocal intelligibility is a matter of bilingualism in the smaller and more dependent of two exogamous communities; Kroeber (1925:308) estimated that the Achumawi were ten times more numerous than the Atsugewi.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The stops and affricate (aside from the marginally contrastive glottal stop) are in three series, plain, aspirated, and laryngealized or glottalized.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The aspirated series is contrastive only syllable-initially and probably derives historically from the voiceless-released first member of a consonant cluster, as in the neighboring Yana language.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The plain-aspirated distinction is neutralized and realized with voiceless release in syllable-final position and before another consonant; the aspirates are much more fortis than this voiceless release.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Syllable-initial plain stops are voiceless (without voiceless release) after long vowel or when geminate (long), and voiced elsewhere.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The laryngealized stops are similar in articulation to the ejective glottalized stops of neighboring languages, but more lenis, that is, not "popped" unless an unusual effort is made at articulating the distinction.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The language has a 5-vowel system /i e a o u/.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Two degrees of length are contrastive for both vowels and consonants.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Long vowels are typically more peripheral and short vowels more centralized, phonetically [ɪ ɛ ʌ ə ʊ].
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The mid vowels /e o/ are probably of secondary origin historically, as in Yana and Atsugewi.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] A short centralized vowel [ə ɨ] appears epenthetically between the consonants of certain prefixes, as in *lhúpta* "let's go!".
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Vowel length assimilates the next successive laryngeal state, that is, the second mora of a long vowel is devoiced before a plain or aspirated consonant (preaspiration) and word finally before silence, and is laryngealized before a laryngealized consonant.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] In upriver dialects vowels and plain stops are more fully voiced.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] In downriver dialects, utterance-final syllables may be devoiced or whispered, especially under interrogative intonation.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] A light syllable consists of a consonant and vowel (CV), and a heavy syllable either contains a long vowel (CVˑ) or is closed with a second consonant (CVC).
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Unlike the neighboring and related language Atsugewi, Achumawi has contrastive high and low tones.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The Achumawi language does not have gender but it has two forms of the copula ("to be") distinguishing animate and inanimate.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The verb stem comprises one or more verb roots plus optional adverbial affixes.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Inflectional affixes on verbs distinguish singular, dual, and plural number, and suffixes may optionally express severality and plurality of nouns.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Many nouns and adjectives are derived from verb stems or participles, and some verb stems are formed by noun incorporation.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] The language has independent adjectives and numerals.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Today, the Achumawi language is extinct.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] Out of an estimated 1500 Achumawi people remaining in northeastern California, perhaps ten spoke the language in 1991, with only eight in 2000.
[src:american-english/achumawi-language] As of 2013, a mobile app was planned for the language.
[src:american-english/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:american-english/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:american-english/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:american-english/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:american-english/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:american-english/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:american-english/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:american-english/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:american-english/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:american-english/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:american-english/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:american-english/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:american-english/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:american-english/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:american-english/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:american-english/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:american-english/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:american-english/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:american-english/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:american-english/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:american-english/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:american-english/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:american-english/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:american-english/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:american-english/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:american-english/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:american-english/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:american-english/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:american-english/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:american-english/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:american-english/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:american-english/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:american-english/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:american-english/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:american-english/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:american-english/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:american-english/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:american-english/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:american-english/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:american-english/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:american-english/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:american-english/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:american-english/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:american-english/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:american-english/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:american-english/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:american-english/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:american-english/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:american-english/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:american-english/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:american-english/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:american-english/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:american-english/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:american-english/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:american-english/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:american-english/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:american-english/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:american-english/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:american-english/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:american-english/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:american-english/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:american-english/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:american-english/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:american-english/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:american-english/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:american-english/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:american-english/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:american-english/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:american-english/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:american-english/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:american-english/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:american-english/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:american-english/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:american-english/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:american-english/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:american-english/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:american-english/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:american-english/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:american-english/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:american-english/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:american-english/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:american-english/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:american-english/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:american-english/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:american-english/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
[src:american-english/american-english] The fronting of the vowels of GOOSE, GOAT, MOUTH, and STRUT tends to also define Southern accents as well as the accents spoken in the "Midland": a vast band of the country that constitutes an intermediate dialect region between the traditional North and South.
[src:american-english/american-english] Western U.S. accents mostly fall under the General American spectrum.
[src:american-english/american-english] Although no longer region-specific, African-American Vernacular English, which remains the native variety of most working- and middle-class African Americans, has a close relationship to Southern dialects and has greatly influenced everyday speech of many Americans, including hip hop culture.
[src:american-english/american-english] Hispanic and Latino Americans have also developed native-speaker varieties of English.
[src:american-english/american-english] The best-studied Latino Englishes are Chicano English, spoken in the West and Midwest, and New York Latino English, spoken in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:american-english/american-english] Additionally, ethnic varieties such as Yeshiva English and "Yinglish" are spoken by some American Orthodox Jews, Cajun Vernacular English by some Cajuns in southern Louisiana, and Pennsylvania Dutch English by some Pennsylvania Dutch people.
[src:american-english/american-english] American Indian Englishes have been documented among diverse Indian tribes.
[src:american-english/american-english] The island state of Hawaii, though primarily English-speaking, is also home to a creole language known commonly as Hawaiian Pidgin, and some Hawaii residents speak English with a Pidgin-influenced accent.
[src:american-english/american-english] In 2024, about 247.7 million Americans, aged five or above, spoke English at home, a majority (77%) of the total U.S. population aged five and over.
[src:american-english/american-english] Of the 50 states, 32 have adopted legislation granting official (or co-official) status to English within their jurisdictions, in some cases as part of what has been called the English-only movement.
[src:american-english/american-english] Typically only "English" is specified, not a particular variety like American English.
[src:american-english/american-english] Puerto Rico is the only United States territory in which another language – Spanish – is the common language at home, in public, and in government.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In the sociolinguistics of the English language, **/æ/ raising**, or **short-*a* raising**, is a phenomenon by which the "short *a*" vowel /æ/ ⓘ, the trap/bath vowel (found in such words as *lack* and *laugh*), is pronounced with a raising of the tongue.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In most American and many Canadian English accents, /æ/ raising is specifically **/æ/ tensing**: a combination of greater raising, fronting, lengthening, and gliding that occurs only in certain phonological environments or certain words.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The most common context for tensing /æ/ throughout North American English, regardless of dialect, is when this vowel appears before a nasal consonant (thus, for example, commonly in *pan*ⓘ, but rarely in *pat*ⓘ).
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The realization of this "tense" (as opposed to "lax") /æ/ includes variants such as [ɛə], [eə], [ɛː], etc., which can depend on the particular dialect or even speaker.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] One common realization is [ɛə], a transcription that will be used throughout this article as a generalized representation of the tensed pronunciation.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Variable raising of /æ/ (and /æɔ/, the MOUTH vowel transcribed with ⟨aʊ⟩ in General American) before nasal consonants also occurs in Australian English.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In Philadelphia, the irregular verbs *began, ran,* and *swam* have [æ].
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In Philadelphia, *bad, mad*, and *glad* alone in this context have [ɛə].
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The untensed /æ/ may be lowered and retracted as much as [ä] in varieties affected by the Low-Back-Merger Shift, mainly predominant in Canada and the American West.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In New York City, certain lexical exceptions exist (like *avenue* being tense) and variability is common before /dʒ/ and /z/ as in *imagine*, *magic*, and *jazz*.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In New Orleans, [ɛə] additionally occurs before /v/ and /z/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Short-*a* (or /æ/) tensing can manifest in a variety of possible ways, including "continuous", discrete, and phonemic ("split").
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In a continuous system, the phoneme /æ/, as in *man*, can be pronounced on a continuum from a lax-vowel pronunciation ⓘ to a tense-vowel pronunciation ⓘ, depending on the context in which it appears.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In a discrete /æ/-tensing system, there is no continuum; any given instance of /æ/ is either tense or lax, with no intermediate realizations.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, in both of these types of system, the degree of raising depends on the context in which the vowel appears, meaning all degrees of tensing are (allophones) of the single "short *a*" phoneme.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In certain traditional regional dialects of American English, however, including the New York City and Philadelphia ones, using a tense short-*a* vowel rather than a lax one could actually change the identity of a word, meaning that "short *a*" sound has been split into two distinct phonemes.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] For instance, in traditional Philadelphia English, the surname *Manning* is pronounced with a lax vowel as /ˈmænɪŋ/, whereas the verb *manning* (as in "He was manning the vehicle") uses the tense vowel as in /ˈmɛənɪŋ/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Therefore, such dialects have a phonemic split of the "short *a*" vowel, sometimes called a "split short-*a* system".
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The relationship between two words (like *Manning* and *manning*) that differ in only a single differentiating sound is known as a minimal pair.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In a North American short-*a* phonemic split system (or, simply, a short-*a* split), the terms "raising" and "tensing" can be used interchangeably.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Phonemic tensing occurs in the dialects of New York City and the Mid-Atlantic States (centering on the cities of Philadelphia and Baltimore).
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] It is similar in its word patterns, but not in its resulting pronunciation, to the TRAP–BATH split of certain British English accents, notably London and other Southeast England dialects, which assigns "broad *a*" of the non-rhotic START class to words that elsewhere retain a "short *a*" sound.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The environment of "broad *a*" overlaps with that of /æ/ tensing in that it occurs before voiceless fricatives in the same syllable and before nasals in certain environments, and both phenomena involve replacement of the short lax vowel /æ/ with a longer and tenser vowel.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, the "broad *a*" is lower and backer than [æ], and the result of /æ/ tensing is higher and fronter.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In some types of West Country English, the result is a distinct phoneme separate from both /æ/ and /ɑː/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] It is also related to the *bad–lad* split of Australian English and some Southern British dialects in which a short flat /æ/ is lengthened to [æː] in some conditions.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The most significant differences from the Philadelphia system described here are that dialects that split *bad–lad* have the "broad *a*" phenomenon, which then prevents the split; 'sad' is long; and lengthening can occur before /ɡ/ and /l/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In the traditional New York accent, the tense /ɛə/ is traditionally an entirely separate phoneme from /æ/ as a result of a phonemic split.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The distribution between /æ/ and /ɛə/ is largely predictable.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In New York City, tensing occurs uniformly in closed syllables before /n/, /m/, voiceless fricatives (/f θ s ʃ/), and voiced stops (/b g d/).
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Tensing occurs much more variably before /dʒ/ and /z/, in both closed and open syllables, such as in *magic* and *jazz*.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In other open syllables, /æ/ tends to stay lax, regardless of the following consonant.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Words with initial /æ/ are usually lax, except for the most common words *aspirin* and *asterisk* with /æ/ vs.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Certain one-off exceptions (The word *avenue* usually has tense /ɛə/, unlike any other case of /æ/ before /v/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The New York City split system has also diffused, often with slightly different conditioning, into Albany, Cincinnati, New Orleans, and nearby parts of New Jersey.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In Northern New Jersey, Labov finds the New York City split system, though with some variability.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] East of the Hackensack River—by Hoboken, Weehawken, and Jersey City—and also in Newark, Labov finds the split to occur with no more variation than in New York City itself.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Between the Hackensack and Passaic Rivers, Labov finds that speakers typically lose the city's function word constraint before nasal consonants.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Thus, *am*, *can* (the verb), *an*, and *and* all typically take on tense /ɛə/, while *had* ordinarily retains lax /æ/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Labov also reports variable tensing in open syllables, resulting in potential tensing of words like *planet* and *fashionable*.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] West of the Passaic River, /æ/ tensing only occurs before nasal consonants.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Like in Northern New Jersey, Labov finds that the New York split system has also diffused in Albany with some alterations.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Although the function is lost in Northern New Jersey, Labov reports that the function constraint is weakened only in Albany.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Thus, *can*, *an*, and *has* may be tensed while *have* and *had* may be lax.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Also, the open syllable constraint is variable in Northern New Jersey, but Labov reports that in Albany, that constraint is absent altogether.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Thus, *national*, *cashew*, *family*, *camera*, *planet*, and *manner* are all tense.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Labov finds the remnants of the New York split system present in the now-declining traditional dialect of Cincinnati, with variations similar to those of Northern New Jersey and Albany.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Like in Albany, the open-syllable constraint is completely absent.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, the function word *and* is reported as being lax.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Labov further reports consistently laxing before /g/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In New York, tensing before voiced fricatives is variable, but it is reported as consistent in Cincinnati.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Labov finds the New York split system in New Orleans with similar variations.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] As in older Cincinnati, tensing may also occur before voiced fricatives.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] As in Northern New Jersey, the function constraint is virtually absent.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, closer to the split of New York City proper, the open syllable constraint is still retained.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Also, the tense variant [ɛə] appears to always be present before voiced fricatives like /v/ and /z/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Philadelphia and Baltimore use a different short-*a* system than New York City, but it is similar in that it is also a split system.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Tensing does not occur before voiced stops and /ʃ/, with the only exceptions being *mad*, *bad*, and *glad*.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Most American and many Canadian English speakers, at the very least, display an /æ/ that is raised (tensed) and diphthongized before the front nasals /m/ and /n/, such as in *camp, man, ram, pan, ran, clamber, Sammy*, which are otherwise lower and laxer.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, they fail to split the "short *a*" into two contrasting phonemes, which the New York, Baltimore, Philadelphia, and Yat accents do.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] A common form is what William Labov calls the "nasal system" in which /æ/ is raised and tensed most severely but not necessarily exclusively before nasal consonants, regardless of whether there is a syllabic or morphemic boundary present.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] More widespread among speakers of the Western United States, Canada, and the southern Midwest is a "continuous system", which also revolves around "short *a*" before nasal consonants but has a less-extreme raising of the tongue than the "nasal system".
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Most varieties of General American English fall under that category.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The pattern most characteristic of Southern American English does not use /æ/ raising at all but uses what has been called the "Southern drawl" instead, with /æ/ becoming in essence a triphthong [æjə].
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, many speakers from the South still use the nasal /æ/-raising system described above, particularly in Charleston, Atlanta, and Florida.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Also, some speakers from the New Orleans area have been reported to have a system that is very similar to the phonemic split of New York.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] For speakers in much of Canada and in the North-Central and the Northwestern United States, a following /ɡ/ (as in *magazine*, *rag*, *bags*, etc.) or /ŋ/ (as in *bang*, *pang*, *gangster*, *angler*, etc.) tenses an /æ/ as much as or more than a following nasal does.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In Wisconsin, Minnesota, and Central Canada, a merger of /æ/ with /eɪ/ before /ɡ/ has been reported, making, for example, *haggle* and *Hegel* homonyms.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In accents that have undergone the Northern Cities Vowel Shift, mostly those of the Inland Northern United States, the phoneme /æ/ is raised and diphthongized in all possible environments: a "general raising" system.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] The Inland North dialect is spoken in such cities as Chicago, Milwaukee, Detroit, Cleveland, Buffalo, Rochester, and Syracuse.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] However, a reversal of the raising (except before nasal consonants) has been observed in at least some of the communities in which it has been documented, including Syracuse and Lansing, Michigan.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In Australian English, /æ/ and the backing diphthong /æɔ/ (which corresponds to /aʊ/ in General American and RP) may be raised to [ɛː, ɛɔ] before nasal consonants.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In the case of /æ/, the raised allophone approaches the DRESS vowel /e/ but is typically somewhat longer, similar to the SQUARE vowel /eː/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] In the case of /æɔ/, it is only the first element that is variably raised, the second element remains unchanged.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] For some speakers this raising is substantial, yet for others it is nonexistent.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] Vowel length has become the main perceptual difference between /æ/ and /e/ when before /n/ or /m/.
[src:american-english/æ-tensing] For example, a word like 'Ben' would be pronounced [ben], while 'ban' would be pronounced [beːn].
